How To make a DOCK distribution for release.

There are four stages each of which is subdivided into steps.

Steps (for everyone) to finalize development:

.  Run all tests including chemgrid and parallel by defining:
   DELPHI_PATH and MPICH_HOME.  Note that mpi test .dockin's need to be
   updated manually for input parameter changes.
   If tests fail, debug and/or update tests.

.  Make sure there are tests for each newly added function.

.  Check for memory leaks and bugs:  make valgrinddock checks the plain dock6
   executable and is a good template.

.  Update manual to reflect new functions and parameters and remove deprecated
   functions and parameters.  Remember to include any new images in the
   docs/images folder.

.  Generate release notes for the web site, eg, docs/new_in_6.13.txt.


Steps to get the repository ready:

.  Coordinate a code freeze with all developers:  releases are planned from
   the master branch; developers can continue work in their branches.

.  Update the version and the release date in src/dock/version.h.

.  Download a clean version of the code on the gold standard machine which was
   hamlet, then as of 6.4 was Glenn, then for 6.8 was george, then for 6.9 was
   Owens: gcc version 4.8.5 20150623 (Red Hat 4.8.5-16) (GCC) RHELS 7.4 (Maipo),
   but as of 6.11 is the Rizzo group's george.ams.sunysb.edu:
   x86_64, gcc version 7.5.0 (Ubuntu 7.5.0-3ubuntu1~18.04)
   which Scott approximates as:  x86_64, gcc version 7.3.0 (GCC)
   Red Hat Enterprise Linux Server release 7.9 (Maipo)
   Compile all executables and run all tests.  If tests fail, debug tests.

.  Update current tutorials to reflect changes in parameter tree and/or changes
   in functionality:  cd install/; make updatedocktutorials; cd ..; git diff;
   amber_scoring_demo and ligand_sampling_demo tutorials mostly live in
   docs/tutorials except for readme's and script_* which live in tutorials.
   solvent_scoring_demo and mpi_demo live in tutorials.
   The above target is suppose to update the dock6 program inputs and outputs
   in one pass (inputs and outputs of other programs need to be manually updated
   if necessary) and invokes target populatedocktutorials to copy files from
   docs/tutorials to tutorials.  This step runs the tutorials, but they should
   still be run during exercising of the pre release; see the next step.
   If things don't look correct after making this once then make it again.
   See the Makefile for elaboration, but note that this can be ignored:
   Could not open ../3_grid/1VRT.rec.nrg for reading. Program will terminate.
   (As of 6.3 the sphere and grid files are from glenn so only the dock ones may
   have to be rerun.  But Scott has not updated these since 6.6 and maybe should
   have since g77 was changed to gfortran.)

.  Download a clean version of the code on Windows, macOS, and Ubuntu OSs.
   Compile all executables, run all tests and tutorials.  If tests fail, debug
   and/or update tests.  Document differences that result from precision issues,
   platform quirks, etc. in install/test/KNOWN_FAILURES.

.  Update docs/tutorials/index.htm and other tutorial web files.

.  Update FAQ current release question to new release.

.  Create new bug fix patches file, eg, docs/bugfixes613/6.13_bugfixes.htm
   and update docs/bugfixes.htm

.  Update docs/index.htm


Steps to make the tarballs from the repository and to post on the server:

.  Update the DISTRIBUTION_TAG in install/Makefile, eg, dock6-13-beta.

.  Generate tarballs for beta testing.  In install/ directory, Makefile target
   archive_export creates tarballs for the distribution and the web site.  Add
   a special license qualification to the README, eg:

   This beta release of DOCK 6 has a special testing-only license that is valid
   for the month of June 2025.

   Put the tarballs on the web, eg, ambermd.org or docking.org, and request
   testing via a private email to friendly users.
   Incorporate feedback per stages above and then proceed to the next step.

.  Tag repository; as of 6.13 use annotated tags for prereleases since
   lightweight tags (no -a in command below) are not permanent:
   git tag -a dock6-13-beta
   git push -u origin dock6-13-beta
   
.  Update the DISTRIBUTION_TAG in install/Makefile, eg, dock6-13-release.

.  Generate tarballs for distribution:  cd install/; make archive_export;

.  Move code tarball to dock.compbio.ucsf.edu /nfs/soft/dock/packages;
   rename file to dock.6.X_source.tar.gz and create symbolic link to
   dock6-latest.tgz for consistency with the web site script.

   scp -p dock6.dock6-13-release.tgz to-ucsf
   ssh to-ucsf
   scp -p ~/tmp/dock6.dock6-13-release.tgz inside-ucsf
   mv -i ~/tmp/dock6.dock6-13-release.tgz dock
   ssh inside-ucsf
   mv -i ~/tmp/dock6.dock6-13-release.tgz dock/dock.6.13_source.tar.gz
   cd /nfs/soft/dock/packages
   cp -ip ~/dock/dock.6.13_source.tar.gz .
   chmod 644 dock.6.13_source.tar.gz
   ln -s dock.6.13_source.tar.gz dock6-latest.tgz

.  The following web site changes occur, as of 6.13, in the ucsf website gitlab:
   git clone https://gitlab.docking.org/kylep/dock.git
   Create a branch then a merge request.

.  Enter dock/html/distributions in the repo.  Update (1 line) version
   number in retrieve_dock_distribution.html :

   cd html/distributions
   vi retrieve_dock_distribution.html

.  Enter dock/cgi-bin/distributions in the repo.
   Open file retrieve_dock_distribution.py.  Change the following line:

      if dock_version[:6] == 'dock_6':
          dock_version = 'dock.6.X'

      where X = newest version

   Open file retrieve_industry_distribution.py.  Change the following line:

      dock6 = ['dock.6.X_source']

      where X = newest version

   cd ../../cgi-bin/distributions
   vi retrieve_dock_distribution.py retrieve_industry_distribution.py

.  Move to dock/html/kuntz.  Update (1 line) index.html to current version :

   cd ../../html/kuntz
   vi index.html

.  Check the diff with the main branch; commit changes.

.  Enter dock/html/kuntz/DOCK_6.  This directory tree is doc/ in our
   repository.  Unwrap the web tarball to update the manual, faq, tutorials, ...
   Check recent weirdness of .htm and .html files and linking.

   cd html/kuntz/DOCK_6
   tar zxf ~/tmp/webarchiveexport.dock6-13-release.tgz
   ll dock6_manual.html dock6_manual.htm
   ll index.htm index.html

.  Check the diff with the main branch; commit changes; push the branch.
   Create a merge request.  For 6.13 I merged my own request.
   Check that the updates are now live on the web site.

.  Test for academic distribution by applying for fake license and going
   through downloading process.  Have an independent third party attempt to
   download code (just in case).  Do Not skip the academic check !:
   https://dock.docking.org/cgi-bin/distributions/retrieve_dock_distribution.py
   We use to test for industry using the password from the test industry license
   "AAAAAAAAA" on the industry license site and then download from the web site
   https://dock.compbio.ucsf.edu/retrieve_industry_distribution.html


Misc. final steps:

.  Send announcements to dock-fans and maybe developers without release notes:
   Subject: Announcement: Release of DOCK 6.13
   Templates:
   https://groups.google.com/g/dock_fans/c/p0zgZoOQTks

.  Send an ad to the Amber reflector, Chimera-users, and CCL.
   For CCL it is best to have two empty lines at the head of the message.

.  Branch repository: Annotated tags are not as convenient for releases.
   So create a branch for archival purposes and plan to use it for bugfixes:
   git checkout -b dock6-13-release
   git push -u origin dock6-13-release

.  Celebrate!

.  Backups are now essentially all in git, but save the dock6 tarballs.

